 {"id":"bd-8jx5","title":"[SUB-EPIC-PHASE] io_uring Reactor (Linux Modern Async I/O)","description":"# Sub-Epic: io_uring Reactor

## Overview

io_uring is Linux's modern async I/O interface (kernel 5.1+), offering significant performance advantages over epoll for certain workloads.

## Why io_uring

1. **True async**: Operations complete in kernel, no syscall per I/O
2. **Batching**: Submit multiple operations with single syscall
3. **Zero-copy**: Can use registered buffers
4. **Lower latency**: Kernel polling mode avoids context switches

## Scope

This sub-epic covers:
- IoUringReactor implementing Reactor trait
- Submission/completion queue management
- Buffer registration for zero-copy
- Polled mode for latency-critical paths

## Design Decisions

### When to Use io_uring vs epoll

| Use Case | Recommended |
|----------|-------------|
| Many idle connections | epoll (lower memory) |
| High throughput file I/O | io_uring |
| Network with many small ops | io_uring (batching) |
| Compatibility (old kernels) | epoll |

### Feature Detection

```rust
fn has_io_uring() -> bool {
    // Check kernel version >= 5.1
    // Try io_uring_setup() and check for features
}
```

## Dependencies

```toml
[target.'cfg(target_os = "linux")'.dependencies]
io-uring = "0.6"  # Safe Rust wrapper
```

## Task Breakdown

1. IoUringReactor core structure
2. Submission queue management
3. Completion queue processing
4. Register/deregister implementation
5. Probing for supported operations
6. Buffer registration API
7. Polled mode option
8. Fallback to epoll on old kernels

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] IoUringReactor implements Reactor trait
- [ ] Passes same tests as EpollReactor
- [ ] Graceful fallback when unavailable
- [ ] Benchmark shows improvement for applicable workloads","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","assignee":"BlackGrove","owner":"jeff141421@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-01-18T06:08:53.981286846Z","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","updated_at":"2026-01-30T04:26:16.923655574Z","closed_at":"2026-01-30T04:26:16.923576758Z","close_reason":"io_uring Reactor fully implemented in src/runtime/reactor/io_uring.rs. IoUringReactor implements Reactor trait (register/modify/deregister/poll/wake). 25+ integration tests pass. Feature-gated (io-uring). Graceful fallback for non-Linux. All acceptance criteria verified.","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"comments":[{"id":1279,"issue_id":"bd-8jx5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Initial scan: Reactor trait in src/runtime/reactor/mod.rs expects register/modify/deregister/poll/wake with Token + Interest. EpollReactor (epoll.rs) implements via polling crate with token->fd bookkeeping; kqueue.rs similar. There is an unused linux.rs stub with outdated Reactor signature (returns Registration) — likely ignore/replace. Integration points: runtime/state.rs + io_driver.rs tests currently instantiate EpollReactor on Linux; io_uring should be optional (feature/cfg) and likely selected via builder/explicit choice with fallback to epoll when unavailable.","created_at":"2026-01-23T03:17:52Z"},{"id":1280,"issue_id":"bd-8jx5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Doc notes (io-uring crate): IoUring::new(entries) requires power-of-two queue size; IoUring::builder() exists for custom params. PollAdd opcode can poll an fd; it is one-shot by default and can be multi-shot via .multi(true) (kernel 5.13+), with CQE flag IORING_CQE_F_MORE indicating more events. PollAdd::new takes flags from poll.h and builds an Entry; user_data can carry Token for completion mapping. (See docs.rs io-uring and PollAdd)","created_at":"2026-01-23T03:18:54Z"},{"id":1281,"issue_id":"bd-8jx5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Eventfd wake path: io_uring::Submitter has register_eventfd/register_eventfd_async + unregister_eventfd. eventfd notifications are only hints (batched CQEs may emit a single eventfd). Likely use eventfd for Reactor::wake() and to interrupt poll loop; still must drain CQ ring on wake.","created_at":"2026-01-23T03:20:28Z"},{"id":1282,"issue_id":"bd-8jx5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Testing note: epoll.rs includes a comprehensive test suite (create/register/modify/deregister/poll/wake, error cases). IoUringReactor should mirror those tests where possible, likely in a new io_uring.rs module with cfg(target_os = linux).","created_at":"2026-01-23T03:20:46Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-8n45","title":"Add negative tests and performance bounds to conformance suite","description":"## Overview

Enhance conformance suite with negative tests (what should NOT work) and performance bounds to ensure runtimes meet expected behavior.

## Requirements

### Negative Tests
Test that incorrect usage is properly rejected:

```rust
conformance_test!(spawn_without_region_fails, |runtime| {
    // Spawning outside a region should fail/panic
    let result = std::panic::catch_unwind(|| {
        runtime.spawn(async { 42 });
    });
    assert!(result.is_err());
});

conformance_test!(double_close_detected, |runtime| {
    // Closing an already-closed region should error
});

conformance_test!(use_after_cancel_detected, |runtime| {
    // Using Cx after cancellation should be handled
});
```

Categories:
1. Invalid region operations (spawn outside region, double close)
2. Invalid obligation handling (use after discharge)
3. Invalid budget operations (negative deadline)
4. Race conditions that should be impossible

### Performance Bounds
Verify operations meet expected performance:

```rust
conformance_test!(spawn_performance_bound, |runtime| {
    let start = Instant::now();
    for _ in 0..1000 {
        runtime.spawn(async {});
    }
    let elapsed = start.elapsed();
    // Spawning 1000 tasks should take < 10ms
    assert!(elapsed < Duration::from_millis(10));
});
```

Bounds to verify:
- spawn: < 10µs per task
- cancel propagation: < 1ms for 100-deep tree
- region close: < 100µs overhead

### Spec Traceability Matrix
Document which spec section each test verifies:

```rust
#[conformance(spec = "3.2.1", requirement = "Region close waits for children")]
fn test_region_close_waits() { ... }
```

## Acceptance Criteria
1. At least 20 negative test cases
2. Performance bounds for critical operations
3. Traceability attribute macro
4. Generated matrix report from tests
5. CI flag to enable/disable performance tests

## Test Requirements
- All negative tests should compile but fail at runtime appropriately
